text.tspan: GPU Accelerated Calculation of Radio Viewsheds

flowRoot.flowPara: Radio viewsheds are, in simple terms, the area of ground that a radio emitter (such as a cell mast) can see. Radio viewshed simulations are useful in helping to plan the placements of these emitters, and are used by telecoms companies, rural ISPs, network researchers, and other indivudals interested in what can be seen from where.

Geoinformatics applications used to generate viewsheds typically rely on the CPU to do their calculations. Because maps of the Earth tend to be implemented as grids of heights, and each cell is independent of the other, GPUs are well suited to calculating viewsheds.

GPUs are designed to operate as grids of slow, simple compute units operating together. As such, GPUs are able to test for visibility of many dozens of cells at once, outstripping the speedier CPUs on account of the massive parallelism they can bring to certain problems.
